On the other hand, the .equals() method compares the actual content of the two strings, character by character. So, if you have two different String objects with the same content, the .equals() method will return true.

Here's an example to illustrate the difference:

```java
String str1 = new String("Hello");
String str2 = new String("Hello");

// Using == operator
if (str1 == str2) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal using =="); // This will NOT be printed
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not equal using ==");
}

// Using .equals() method
if (str1.equals(str2)) {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are equal using .equals()"); // This will be printed
} else {
    System.out.println("str1 and str2 are not equal using .equals()");
}
```

In summary, you should always use the .equals() method to compare strings in Java. The == operator should be used when you want to compare if two references are pointing to the same object in memory, not for comparing the content of the objects.

